  <title>The Little Computer - Assembly</title>
  <p>The Little Computer supports an <xref ref="programming-languages_assembly-languages" text="custom">assembly language</xref> that can make it easier for humans
    to write and read programs. In addition to replacing numeric commands like <q>1XX</q> or <q>902</q>
    with abbreviated English commands like <q>ADD</q> or <q>OUT</q>, Little Computer assembly allows us to
    think at a slightly more abstract level. Instead of remembering specific memory addresses so we can say <em><q>add
    the value from location 10</q></em>, we can name memory locations and then say things like <em><q>add
    X</q></em>. This video introduces it:</p>

  <video xml:id="gg4siPI0sdk" youtube="gg4siPI0sdk" width="100%" />
  <p>You can try the assembler here: <url href="external/LittleComputer/littleComputerAssembler.html"
      visual="external/LittleComputer/littleComputerAssembler.html">Launch the Little Computer assembler</url>  <em>(Control
    or Command click to open in a new window)</em></p>
  <p>To test out a program after assembling it, use the Little Computer: <url
      href="external/LittleComputer/littleComputer.html" visual="external/LittleComputer/littleComputer.html">Launch the
    Little Computer</url>  </p>
